This course, “Impressionism: European Art: 1860-1900,” surveys the movement's major contexts and proponents - Magnet, Monet, Morisot, Cezanne, Gauguin, Van Gogh, Rodin - from its 1860s origins to its demise in the 1890s and then later global adaptations until WWI. It emphasizes Impressionism's critical reception and the historical conditions allowing France to claim the emergence of early Modernism. The class focuses on considering how an art of vision and light figures the complexities of history and politics and especially the revolutions that marked the period; the gendered and sexual politics of Impressionism's obsession with the nude female body; and, how the invention of the new technologies and media effected the development of modern art. Throughout the course, students will also analyze the effects the rapidly changing social and cultural fabric of Paris had on artistic developments. &#8232;&#8232;

This class is a “fantastic” and “very interesting” course that “covers the subject matter in great detail.” Students collectively felt that they “gained a very good understanding of the time period” and appreciated that this discipline was made “very accessible to those who had never studied it before.” &#8232;

Professor Dombrowski “is interesting to listen to” and is “able to create interest and satisfy expectations created.” While one student believed that Professor Dombrowski “needs to work on his time management,” other students described him as both a “very engaging professor” and a “dynamic leader.” Because the professor “injects enthusiasm into the classes,” “it is impossible to tune out during his class.” Students generally felt the class educated them sufficiently on the material, in part due to Professor Dombrowski’s obvious “passion for the subject matter.” Lectures are structured “by concept, not time period,” so while Professor Dombrowski analyzes the same paintings throughout the course, he interprets them differently based on the new concept, making “every lesson…exciting and fresh.” With especially “stimulating lectures,” one student asserted that, “the class made me question my whole major because [Professor Dombrowski] stimulated my interest in Art History so much. If I remember one class and one professor from Penn, it will be this class. 10 STARS.” &#8232;

&#8232;This class involves a significant amount of reading and a “fair amount of work,” making it “difficult and worthwhile.” Students typically found that “recitations stimulate thought-provoking discussions,” but others felt “readings were at times tedious and unrewarding.” Others felt the readings were “very well selected” but mentioned they might “prefer TAs that have already taken the course.” Additionally, this elective’s final exam and paper over the course of the same week seemed “redundant.” Some expressed that there was some “repetitiveness in assignments/tests throughout the course,” however, one student summarizes the class’ overall sentiment by saying “the class was well taught, the readings were relevant, and the assignments were appropriate to encourage learning.”
